<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.nj.com/newsflash/washington/index.ssf?/cgi-free/getstory_ssf.cgi?a0705_BC_Attacks-Nuclear&&news&newsflash-washington">www.nj.com/newsflash/wash...washington</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
The Nuclear Regulatory Commission says controlling the airspace over atomic power plants is the best available way to prevent a terrorist attack. <br>
<br>
The agency also again acknowledged that the plants were not built to withstand a fully fueled jetliner crashing into them. <br>
<br>
&quot;The commission believes that the nation's efforts associated with protecting against terrorist attacks by air should be directed toward enhancing security at airports and on airplanes,&quot; the director of the NRC's Office of Nuclear Reactor Regulation wrote a whistle-blower group. <br>
<br>
Samuel J. Collins said the NRC, the Federal Aviation Administration and Defense Department have discussed the idea of protecting air space over the power reactors and other sensitive sites. <br>
