<br>
Nuclear security still lax, report says<br>
<br>
Armed staff cut by 40% at sites<br>
<br>
By Michael Kilian<br>
Washington Bureau<br>
<br>
August 20, 2002<br>
<br>
WASHINGTON -- Security at the Energy Department's 30 nuclear weapons laboratories, manufacturing plants and storage sites remains dangerously lax, according to a congressional report to be released Tuesday, rendering them vulnerable to terrorist attack despite government pledges after the Sept. 11 attacks to improve security.<br>
<br>
Overall security forces at these facilities have been slashed by nearly 40 percent, falling from 7,091 in 1992 to 4,262 last year, and the Department of Energy, which runs the facilities, has failed to adequately upgrade their security regulations since Sept. 11, the report charges. The White House has twice in the past year declined to spend additional large sums of money that were requested to improve security at the sites, the report says, even though the Energy Department has described such funds as &quot;urgently needed.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I believe we continue to face an unacceptable level of risk that terrorists could successfully target these sites,&quot; said Rep. Edward Markey (D-Mass.), who is releasing the report. &quot;Nearly a year after Sept. 11, we should not face such a sorry state of affairs.&quot; Markey is co-chair of Congress' Bipartisan Task Force on Non-proliferation.<br>
<br>
The Bush administration denies that it is allowing security at the sites to lapse. White House Office of Management and Budget spokeswoman Amy Call said the Energy Department still has funds available for security purposes, and added that security needs will be addressed further in the president's next budget.<br>
<br>
The National Nuclear Security Administration, which is part of the Energy Department, has a $560 million budget--35 percent higher than last year, Call added.<br>
<br>
The debate over the government's 30 nuclear institutions is part of a broader re-examination of security at virtually all the nation's major facilities, from airports to military bases to dams to ports, in the wake of Sept. 11.<br>
<br>
Because they handle lethal radioactive material that could be turned into weapons by terrorists, nuclear facilities are drawing greater attention. The Energy Department has recently decided to move part of the Los Alamos National Laboratory from New Mexico to the Nevada desert, despite official claims that the security at Los Alamos is adequate.<br>
<br>
Illinois' Argonne National Laboratory East has abolished all 33 of the armed guard positions it had in 1992, and now employs 34 unarmed security guards. &quot;The security personnel at Argonne do not carry weapons,&quot; said Argonne spokeswoman Catherine Foster. &quot;Deadly force is not authorized.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cuts in security defended<br>
<br>
Argonne performs research with nuclear material, she said, but it no longer operates a nuclear reactor and does not work with nuclear weapons, eliminating the need for guards with the authority to fire weapons. The type and amount of nuclear materials at Argonne East are now rated a lower risk Class IV, whereas they used to be rated at a higher risk Class II, she said.<br>
<br>
Markey said his 22-page report is based on unclassified information provided by the Department of Energy in 250 pages of responses to questions he submitted on nuclear facility security earlier this year.<br>
<br>
Markey said there is enough weapons-grade plutonium and highly enriched uranium at 10 of the labs to build a crude but workable atomic bomb or one or more &quot;dirty bombs&quot; that could explode radioactive particles over an area.<br>
<br>
According to the report, over the past decade, the armed security forces at Los Alamos were cut from 322 to 255; at Colorado's Rocky Flats from 380 to 154; at California's Livermore lab from 141 to 124; and at Oak Ridge, Tenn., from 47 to 17. Nationwide, the number of armed security forces has decreased from 4,471 to 2,472, a drop of 45 percent.<br>
<br>
Bryan Wilkes, a spokesman for the National Nuclear Security Administration, said Markey's figures on armed security guards do not reflect recent increases in security staff at some facilities. But he said he could not provide numbers of additional guards because that information is secret.<br>
<br>
Wilkes added that most of the cuts in armed personnel were made during the Clinton administration and in part reflect the decrease in the U.S. nuclear arsenal that followed the end of the Cold War.<br>
<br>
Last January, Gen. John Gordon, then director of the National Nuclear Security Administration, declared in a public statement that &quot;allegations that the Department of Energy has lax security at its nuclear weapons facilities are false and misleading.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We aggressively protect our people, facilities and materials, and we display a formidable security posture to potential attackers,&quot; Gordon said.<br>
<br>
But in March, Markey said, the Energy Department submitted a request for $379.7 million in supplemental funds to the White House budget office &quot;to meet urgent and compelling requirements for safeguards and security, emergency response and energy security and assurance activities.&quot;<br>
<br>
Funding not approved<br>
<br>
The White House instead approved only $26 million in supplemental funds for the agency, he added.<br>
<br>
Then, in July, Congress approved and sent to the president a $5.1 billion spending bill for various purposes, including $360 million for Energy Department security. But last week during an economic forum in Texas, Bush announced he would not spend the $5.1 billion, citing the need for fiscal responsibility.<br>
<br>
Call, the budget office spokeswoman, said the Energy Department still has money left from an earlier spending bill and added that the White House is awaiting the results of the agency's vulnerability assessment of its security needs before proceeding with more spending.<br>
<br>
As for the $5.1 billion package, Call said it was an unprecedented &quot;all-or-nothing measure&quot; that included not only security funds for the agency but also money for such items as &quot;worm storage at the Smithsonian Institution.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The president felt it was wrong to force his hand to spend the money this way,&quot; she said, adding that the White House has been assured that &quot;the weapons complexes are secure.&quot;<br>
